iterature from the 'Other Europe' to Western Europe, the United States, and back illuminates the intertwined fabrics of Cold War literary cultures. Perceiving tamizdat as both a literary and a social phenomenon, the book focuses on how individuals participated in this border-crossing activity and used secretive channels to guarantee the free flow of literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aRussian literaturexPublishingxForeign countriesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnderground literaturezSoviet UnionxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aCensorship, Cold War, East and West, Foreign relations, Freedom of expression, Literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078054340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963386023640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633860236423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633860236/original  a978-3-11-078054-3  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK